english:
  title: 'Early Rising: Combing Hair in Emulation of Su Shi'
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The lamplight gutters, threading jade blossoms,
    The sea spreads wide, cradling the golden crow of dawn.
    Sitting in silence, I hold my breath long,
    My hands trace the elixir field below the navel.

    Thinning hair at my temples—a thousand tangled strands,
    The old comb draws through like the slant of a crescent moon.
    With each stroke, they fall like gentle snow,
    As if the spring wind itself were sweeping frost away.

    Golden wire refined again and yet again—
    A hundred times worked, and still not overdone.
    Does such care not lighten the body and refresh the spirit?
    Does it not also lengthen the span of years?

    The old rooster dusts itself in dung,
    The weary horse rolls in the desert sand—
    Even they know how to nurture their own nature.
    This wisdom I learned from the Eastern Slope.
  footnotes:
    - Su Shi (蘇軾, 1037–1101), known as the Eastern Slope Sage (東坡), was a renowned Song Dynasty poet and official who wrote extensively on health cultivation and simple living.
    - The 'elixir field' (丹田) is a concept from Taoist internal alchemy, believed to be a point of vital energy cultivation located below the navel.
    - The poem playfully contrasts the refinement of grooming and breathing exercises with animals' simpler methods of self-care, suggesting that cultivating one's nature takes many forms.
